d evolution more like a kind of belief, not like a scientific proved fact. This would be the fact that there are no transitional fossils. I also, in some poor research that I made, I found out that absolute dating is note quite reliable, and also it creates possibility of many more interpretations. Any suggestions on those two topics? (Especially scientific works that would treat this topic.)"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7e438eb7734383a0991df392c3dd7650?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1154,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1154/artaxerxe","reputation":124,"display_name":"artaxerxe"},"score":0,"post_id":2927,"edited":false,"creation_date":1447791484,"comment_id":68789,"body":"N.B. I don&#39;t want to challenge you, although maybe that&#39;s an implication of my question. I&#39;m mainly in search of some material on this issue that makes approaches from a scientific point of view as much as possible. Thanks. :)."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1342681984,"creation_date":1342681330,"body":"<p>You won't find a good book that presents the 'weaknesses' of the theory of evolution, and for good reason. There has to date been no convincing challenge to the theory, whilst it has been supported by experimental and circumstantial evidence as well as clear logic over and over and over again, as well as actually being observed taking place numerous times. The closest to what looking for is a book which presents our best understanding of how evolution works, or which discusses competing ideas about <em>how<\/em> evolution works - there's no question about whether it works.<\/p>\n\n<p>The Selfish Gene by Richard Dawkins, whilst it contains some errors, has some very clear thinking about evolution in it, and in particular explains why group selection is a misguided idea.<\/p>\n\n<p>The Logic of Chance: The Nature and Origin of Biological Evolution by Eugene Koonin is a more up-to-date coverage of our current understanding of evolution, in particular with insights from modern genomics.<\/p>\n\n<p>There are plenty of terrible books about the weaknesses of evolution, but they are deeply flawed. Pick one and I'll be happy to debunk it for you.<\/p>\n","answer_id":2927,"question_id":2926,"up_vote_count":16,"last_edit_date":1342681984},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6a37a096cfb6f7b8e40e4950dc1a9658?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1156,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1156/oldcurmudgeon","reputation":217,"display_name":"OldCurmudgeon"},"score":10,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1670879794aed7c23742e5b1f759be94?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1136,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1136/tomd","reputation":2087,"display_name":"TomD"},"score":3,"post_id":2928,"edited":false,"creation_date":1342700225,"comment_id":4270,"body":"+ 1 for &#39;He is definitely an atheist&quot;"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1342697108,"creation_date":1342697108,"body":"<p>Almost anything by <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Richard-Dawkins/e/B000AQ3RBI\">Richard Dawkins<\/a> would be excellent value. I especially like his <a href=\"http://rads.stackoverflow.com/amzn/click/0393316823\">Climbing Mount Improbable<\/a> as a short but gripping account of why evolution can achieve such astoundingly complex results.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Richard Dawkins<\/strong> (from my link above)<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Richard Dawkins taught zoology at the University of California at Berkeley and at Oxford University and is now the Charles Simonyi Professor of the Public Understanding of Science at Oxford.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>He is definitely an atheist.<\/p>\n","answer_id":2928,"question_id":2926,"up_vote_count":10},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fdd630f72eef3790bfb4ef38d08c7f85?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG