 higher energy $\\ce{O2}$ as a waste product? Is there so much energy available for photosynthesis that plants can afford to waste some of it producing $\\ce{O2}$ simply to have enough carbon atoms to store energy via sugars?<\/p>\n","question_id":28587,"tags":["metabolism","thermodynamics","carbohydrates"],"score":4,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":91,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1424100057},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/D00wA.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":13495,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13495/aalawlx","reputation":206,"display_name":"Aalawlx","accept_rate":86},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":3,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1424169528,"creation_date":1424169252,"body":"<p>First of all: Honey is not a byproduct of bees - it's their main and most important product which stores energy for the bee hive for the time when no flowers are available.<\/p>\n\n<p>Honey itself consists (according to the USDA database) to about 99.5% of water and sugars (82.5% sugars, 17% water). The sugars are mostly fructose and glucose, but also some other mono- di and tri-saccherides in traces. See reference 1 for details. It also contains trace amounts of vitamins and minerals, see table from the Wikipedia on <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Honey\" rel=\"nofollow\">Honey<\/a>:<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/SLS3b.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p>The protein content varies between honey sample but is somewhere in the range between 0.2 and 0.5% (see also reference 1). The proteins come from flowers (pollen incorporated into the honey) as well as from the bees (see reference 2). Paper 1 lists a number of enzymes as most common bee proteins in the honey, but doesn't go into much more details here. These are invertase, diastase, glucose oxidase and catalase. <\/p>\n\n<p>You could now go into the sequence databases (<em>Apis mellifera<\/em> has been complete sequenced) and look up the sequence information of the enzymes. Information can be found <a href=\"http://hymenopteragenome.org/beebase/\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a> and <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/genome?term=apis%20mellifera\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>References:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.directupload.net/file/d/3901/tt4jklhg_pdf.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">A review of the analytical methods to determine the geographical and\nbotanical origin of honey<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.directupload.net/file/d/3901/rvokxgcy_pdf.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">Source of the honey protein responsible for apple juice\nclarification<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n","answer_id":28633,"question_id":28622,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1424169528}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/28622/has-the-protein-composition-with-identification-in-honey-and-other-honeybee-by","last_activity_date":1424169528,"creation_date":1424134680,"answer_count":1,"title":"Has the protein composition (with identification) in honey and other honeybee byproducts been studied?","body":"<p>I am interested in studying honey and other honeybee byproducts.  I have not been able to find sequence or structure records for any of the contents of honey.<\/p>\n\n<p>In particular, I want to study the protein sequence and structure and the amino acid compositions within honey.<\/p>\n\n<p>Has any of this data been produced and published in any databases or research papers?<\/p>\n","question_id":28622,"tags":["proteins","dna-sequencing","3d-structure","protein-structure"],"score":6,"accepted_answer_id":28633,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":78,"up_vote_count":6,"last_edit_date":1424148268},{