,"edited":false,"creation_date":1423747458,"comment_id":46947,"body":"@ChrisStronks Shall we debate about this in the <a href=\"http://chat.stackexchange.com/rooms/21066/discussion-between-wysiwyg-and-chris-stronks\">chat<\/a>"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1423833596,"creation_date":1423731876,"body":"<p>Flux is defined as amount of heat transferred per unit area per unit time. <\/p>\n\n<p>Our body does not perceive heat flux. It perceives temperature and tries to adjust heat exchange mechanisms until thermal homeostasis is achieved (in all warm blooded animals). This is a feedback controlled process.<\/p>\n\n<p>If it were to measure heat flux then the body cannot sense if it is at 47\u2070C and the environment is at 60\u2070C or if it is at 37\u2070C and the environment is at 50\u2070C. The heat sensors in our body have evolved to function at 37\u2070C. Their conformation changes with increase/decrease in temperature thereby opening or closing the ion channels. The conformation is a function of temperature. If you put that channel in 45\u2070C and try to measure a temperature higher that that then it wont work in the same way.<\/p>\n\n<p>Body function and metabolism are sensitive to absolute temperature. Also see <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/21258/how-does-temperature-influence-the-rate-of-protein-degradation/24218#24218\">this<\/a> post. <\/p>\n\n<p>So while temperature sensing is absolutely necessary even for cold-blooded animals, plants and other organisms, there is no mechanism to measure heat flux. You can just measure the effect of heat not the flow of heat. For e.g. you cannot say if a body is cooling more rapidly than the other just by perceiving it for a short duration. It is possible to consciously calculate heat flux but it is neither measured nor (afaik) is fed in as a parameter to any control systems that regulate body temperature.<\/p>\n","answer_id":28527,"question_id":28520,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1423833596},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":6,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":28530,"edited":false,"creation_date":1423745461,"comment_id":46936,"body":"&quot;I say yes, heat-flux is definitely sensed as it per definition generates a temperature difference.&quot; I disagree with this statement. The temperature difference causes heat flux and not vice versa. Heat flux is dependent on the nature of the material and this may differ for skin types. But ultimately thermal equilibrium is reached."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":28530,"edited":false,"creation_date":1423745571,"comment_id":46937,"body":"I can understand the point on adaptation that you raise but temperature ultimately affects metabolism. Adaptation has a limit. For pain sensations the responses can be heightened if the tissue is already sensitized. Temperature difference is sensed but this doesnt mean that the response will be the same as long as the difference is the same. The operations of temperature sensor is non-linear. Nothing in biology is linear."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":0,"post_id":28530,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"edited":false,"creation_date":1423745772,"comment_id":46939,"body":"Your first comment: (1) no, nothing needs to be fixed - when equilibrium is reached, you don&#39;t feel temperature differences, that&#39;s the whole point. (2) Heat flux is definitely dependent on the material, see my answer last paragraph. With regard to your second comment: (3) Adaptation has of course limits. Everything has. I am talking physiological conditions. (4) Of course pain increases on top of an already existing pain. It is a difference! (5) Many sensory systems are non linear! I have <b>never<\/b> mentioned linearity. Don&#39;t put words in my mouth. I don&#39;t see any points in your two comments."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":28530,"edited":false,"creation_date":1423745964,"comment_id":46940,"body":"when you say that absolute temperature doesn&#39;t matter as long as the temperature difference is the same means: <code>f(T\u2081-T\u2082)=f(T\u2081)-f(T\u2082)<\/code> which denotes linearity. I am saying that this is not true. The function does not behave the same at all points as long as temperature difference is the same"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":0,"post_id":28530,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biol