":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11841/one-face","reputation":2241,"display_name":"One Face","accept_rate":73},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1423730473,"creation_date":1423730473,"body":"<p>One mechanism through which low temperatures cause pain is through vasoconstriction.<\/p>\n\n<p>Cold environment causes constriction of blood vessels in the periphery. This will cause decreased blood flow and the muscles will cramp due to lack of oxygen. The cramping is due to the accumulation of lactic acid (due to activation of anaerobic pathways of metabolism) and carbon dioxide. Both these chemicals will lower the pH which cause pain.<\/p>\n","answer_id":28526,"question_id":28467,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/28467/how-and-why-can-cold-inflict-pain","last_activity_date":1423730473,"creation_date":1423543431,"answer_count":2,"title":"How and why can cold inflict pain?","body":"<p>I was carrying a can of very cold liquid, had something heavy in my other hand so couldn't switch hands. After a few minutes, I started to feel very intense pain. I was very surprised. cold is just atoms moving slower. This makes more sense if you think about how heat, or burns can cause pain. But heat can cook tissue and disable it, it makes sense it would hurt. <\/p>\n","question_id":28467,"tags":["pain","heat"],"score":5,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":55,"up_vote_count":5},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e5fe0997d850b57fe0c540dae6c6b387?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":13404,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13404/harold","reputation":71,"display_name":"Harold"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"use