other side of a King-sized mattress. <\/p>\n\n<p>It appears to be a worm wrapped in a cocoon. It is pretty short, being small enough to fit inside an eye cream container.<\/p>\n\n<p>The creature is a pale yellow-white/cream, with brownish-red tips on each end (unless it can somehow turn around without exiting its casing). It looks from the side as if it has a rather flat face, one that comes to a slight bump at the bottom, but is pretty much flat. The casing is light grey, with some small portions that appear to be almost the same color as the organism, just slightly darker. There is an opening at each end of the casing, which the organism uses to slide slightly out. It has never fully come out of the casing. The edges of the openings at each end are white. The casing seems to either be made out of or covered in dust.<\/p>\n\n<p>It can create a substance that is sticky and strong enough to support its weight. I cannot tell if the substance is created by the 'worm', or the 'cocoon'. A thread at each end of the casing is connected to the side of the container by the substance. When I accidentally detached one end of the casing, the entire thing began to shake violently when held so that one end was hanging. It wouldn't stop until I had turned it so that both ends were touching the side of the container. Within minutes, though, it had reattached the broken end. <em>Minutes<\/em>. Not hours, but <em>one minute<\/em>.<\/p>\n\n<p>The holes at each end of the cocoon can either grow or shrink closed. I believe this allows us to tell which opening is in use. If it is nearly shut, it will come out the other end.<\/p>\n\n<p>It appears to be nocturnal, since it doesn't move during the day, but it is very active at night. It also appears to react to light. If some is put on it, it will poke out to look around.  <\/p>\n\n<p>It has survived for four days straight without food, as far as we know. We put a small piece of lettuce in with it. However, there are two small, brownish things on the bottom of the container. This may be its excrement.<\/p>\n\n<p>The creature moves by reaching out with its 'tentacle/worm', grabbing onto something (including the ground), and pulling itself forward.<\/p>\n\n<p>I cannot tell if the creature is attaching to the container's side to climb, or because it is morphing. If that is the case, then the outer shell may be a cocoon. It did detach itself from the side of the container, and first hid under a ledge of lettuce, but now has wrapped itself in lettuce.<\/p>\n\n<p>Thank you in advance for helping me figure out what this thing is. I haven't ever seen anything like it, and it may be interesting to keep alive and study/watch.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>To summarize: can someone please help me identify this creature?<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/eXbpL.jpg\" alt=\"Creature\"><\/p>\n","question_id":28479,"tags":["species-identification"],"score":14,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":365,"up_vote_count":14,"last_edit_date":1423587679},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e6e8cc1cfea0efb8c5c77445bc064298?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":13407,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13407/warrenu","reputation":26,"display_name":"WarrenU"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"score":6,"post_id":28484,"edited":false,"creation_date":1423597444,"comment_id":46795,"body":"The drone bee is haploid, they only have 1 copy of each chromosome, so the chromosomes aren&#39;t duplicated. See <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haplodiploidy\" rel=\"nofollow\">this<\/a>."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/11ecb2130d870caa97f33b9e9e658e19?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4109,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4109/resonating","reputation":3125,"display_name":"Resonating"},"score":0,"post_id":28484,"edited":false,"creation_date":1423603481,"comment_id":46797,"body":"In the general case sex chromosomes in animals are different from the human XX/XY. Birds, some reptiles, some insects use ZW, where the female is ZW and the male is ZZ. Others use XO where XX is female and X is male. There are others. Fungi have hundreds of &#39;sexes&#39; because they have a particularly weird system."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/041315a27276228cff7a5bec5d1f8d5e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":13419,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13419/yidryi","reputation":71,"display_name":"yidryi"},"score":7,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"score":0,"post_id":28516,"edited":false,"creation_date":1423690836,"comment_id":46874,"body":"Do you have a source for the diploid males?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/041315a27276228cff7a5bec5d1f8d5e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":13419,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13419/yidryi","reputation":71,"display_name":"yidryi"},"score":1,"post_id":28516,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"edited":false,"creation_date":1423690958,"comment_id":46875,"body":"Here is one source <a href=\"http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2FBF01240420\" rel=\"nofollow\">link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2FBF01240420<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"score":0,"post_id":28516,"edited":false,"creation_date":1423692132,"comment_id":46879,"body":"That&#39;s interesting, looks like 50% of all larva in those colonies are male, that would seriously handicap those colonies. Since the odds of diploid males goes up when inbreeding happens, do bees have some sort of defense against inbreeding? How many versions of the CSD gene are there? Because more versions would lead to reduced chances of diploid males. Also makes me want to know how the bee detects heterozygosity vs homozygosity."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/041315a27276228cff7a5bec5d1f8d5e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":13419,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13419/yidryi","reputation":71,"display_name":"yidryi"},"score":2,"post_id":28516,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"edited":false,"creation_date":1423693646,"comment_id":46880,"body":"Yes the honey bee csd is highly polymorphic, which reduces the odds of inbreeding (e.g. <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1626638/\" rel=\"nofollow\">ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1626638<\/a>). It&#39;s an interesting point within the context of bottlenecked populations (e.g. imagine an invasive bee swarm transferred by boat that has no conspecifics around) because, as you point out, if the population has low csd variability then it increases the probability that a diploid bee will be an inviable male rather than a viable worker. But as queens mate with multiple drones, a single invading queen can have multiple csd alleles in her spermatheca."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/041315a27276228cff7a5bec5d1f8d5e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":13419,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13419/yidryi","reputation":71,"display_name":"yidryi"},"score":2,"post_id":28516,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"edited":false,"creation_date":1423693977,"comment_id":46882,"body":"Also note that diploid honey bee drones can be viable if they (somehow) make it to maturity without being killed by workers (e.g. <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16475107\" rel=\"nofollow\">ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16475107<\/a>). It looks like workers tell diploid and haploid males apart by pheromones."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SDypL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9458,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9458/hde-226868","reputation":692,"display_name":"HDE 226868","accept_rate":100},"score":0,"post_id":28516,"edited":false,"creation_date":1423694505,"comment_id":46883,"body":"@yidryi Feel free to add those links into the answer."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1423695505,"creation_date":1423690716,"body":"<p>The short answer, which has already been pointed out by user137, is that females are diploid while males are haploid. Bees do not have sex chromosomes per se; rather sex is determined by the <em>csd<\/em> gene on chromosome III (<em>csd<\/em> stands for complementary sex determination). Diploid bees that are heterozygous at the <em>csd<\/em> locus (i.e. contain two different alleles (versions of a gene) for <em>csd<\/em>) are female (workers).<\/p>\n\n<p>Bees that are haploid at the <em>csd<\/em> are males. Interestingly, diploid bees that are homozygous at the <em>csd<\/em> (i.e. contain two copies of the same <em>csd<\/em> allele) are also males. But in the honey bee, these bees do not survive as they are killed by workers before they mature. In some other haplodiploid species, however, both haploid and diploid males are viable (<a href=\"http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2FBF01240420\" rel=\"nofollow\">the bumble bee <em>Bombus terrestris<\/em> for example<\/a>). Also note that diploid honey bee drones can be viable if they (somehow) make it to maturity without being killed by workers (e.g. <a href=\"http://ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16475107\" rel=\"nofollow\">see here<\/a>).<\/p>\n","answer_id":28516,"question_id":28484,"up_vote_count":7,"last_edit_date":1423695505}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/28484/how-can-a-drone-be-male","last_activity_date":1423695505,"creation_date":1423596976,"answer_count":1,"title":"How can a drone be male?","body":"<p>A drone bee is male and is the product of only a queen bee. How is it that the drone bee can be male. I know that a drone is produced by an unfertilized egg, but this does not explain where the two X chromosomes come from. To me, this means that the one X chromosome from the queen must some how be duplicated.<\/p>\n","question_id":28484,"tags":["zoology","reproductive-biology"],"score":4,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":true,"view_count":125,"up_vote_count":5},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0d5e678991b454a8c183888bc135f475?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":746,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/746/jake","reputation":172,"display_name":"Jake"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f437d9a11deebd214089822c26197f35?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3553,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3553/james","reputation":4533,"display_name":"James","accept_rate":83},"score":0,"post_id":5268,"edited":false,"creation_date":1423657259,"comment_id":46837,"body":"Its unclear what you&#39;re asking. Do you want to know about the biochemistry of the cell cycle or how evolution drove organisms to replicate? &quot;Is there some sort of stimulant in the environment?&quot; Nutrition is required and some molecules can encourage rapid division. &quot;A chemical reaction that causes it?&quot; A complex biochemical one yes. &quot;Is is there a physical or emotional motivation?&quot; No. &quot;Is it by choice?&quot; No."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1MUb2.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1306,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1306/terdon","reputation":9339,"display_name":"terdon","accept_rate":73},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0d5e678991b454a8c183888bc135f475?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":746,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/746/jake","reputation":172,"display_name":"Jake"},"score":0,"post_id":5270,"edited":false,"creation_date":1353420857,"comment_id":7548,"body":"So in your metaphor, rolling down slope is the process of replication?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1MUb2.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1306,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1306/terdon","reputation":9339,"display_name":"terdon","accept_rate":73},"score":1,"post_id":5270,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0d5e678991b454a8c183888bc135f475?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":746,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/746/jake","reputation":172,"display_name":"Jake"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1353441100,"comment_id":7556,"body":"@Jake, yes, the point I am trying to make is that replication is the natural state of cells and needs to be actively prevented for the cells to not proliferate."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1423688176,"creation_date":1353411558,"body":"<p>This is a very interesting question but the answer (or as much of the answer as is known) can fill a few books. There are many many signals that control cell division. <\/p>\n\n<p>As a horrible simplification, the cell can be compared to a car parked on a slope with a driver's foot on the brake. If she lifts her foot, the car will roll downhill. In the cell, there are various proteins (<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P53\" rel=\"nofollow\">P53<\/a> is the most famous) that have their metaphorical foot on the brake. Various external and internal stimuli can cause these proteins to stop suppressing replication and the cell will then continue its cycle and replicate. <\/p>\n\n<p>So, a cell's \"natural state\" is to replicate, there is a complex network of interacting factors (primarily proteins) that actively block replication in resting cells. When the conditions are \"right\" (what that means depends on the cell in question) the block is removed and the cell replicates.<\/p>\n","answer_id":5270,"question_id":5268,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1423688176},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4e8d0828732c8eb54a0335e7eab1ec9f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":112,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/112/michael-kuhn","reputation":3583,"display_name":"Michael Kuhn","accept_rate":75},"score":2,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0d5e678991b454a8c183888bc135f475?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":746,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/746/jake","reputation":172,"display_name":"Jake"},"score":0,"post_id":5272,"edited":false,"creation