e.com/users/69/rory-m","reputation":9094,"display_name":"Rory M","accept_rate":88},"edited":false,"creation_date":1353430853,"comment_id":7555,"body":"@RoryM Thinking out loud: Due to pre-perception of a living thing, defining it with &quot;ability to reproduce&quot; seems to suggest that when the thing reproduce, it does so under its controlled will. However if i am asked WHY a kitchen sponge absorbs water with its ability to do so, I am unlikely to suggest that the sponge has a will. In a way, the sponge MUST absorb water. So to answer the &quot;why&quot;, either living thing MUST reproduce, or the more approperiate question becomes, &quot;does living thing desire to reproduce&quot; or &quot;can living thing inherently stop (temporarily) reproduction?&quot; Hope I make sense..."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/08613e0b782cdf2bb8f2501cae9bdc5d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":806,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/806/armatus","reputation":5317,"display_name":"Armatus","accept_rate":81},"score":0,"post_id":5272,"edited":false,"creation_date":1353503539,"comment_id":7568,"body":"In your words, living things &quot;must&quot; reproduce - they have the ability to do so, and if the environment allows it, reproduction will spontaneously (i.e. without &quot;will&quot;, &quot;intention&quot; or &quot;motivation&quot;) happen. Compared to the original first molecule that had this ability, even the simplest cell is an incredibly complex organism with highly sophisticated control mechanisms which integrate all the necessary requirements for favourable reproduction and scan the environment (both internal and external) for these conditions."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1353417981,"creation_date":1353417981,"body":"<p>If there are enough nutrients, a unicellular organism will \"eat\" and grow until it reaches a certain size. Through different mechanisms, it can sense that it is large enough and has enough metabolites to divide. Then, the organism will duplicates its DNA, separate the duplicated DNA and divide. (This is called <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fission_%28biology%29\" rel=\"nofollow\">fission<\/a> for prokaryotes.)<\/p>\n\n<p>So why does it happen? One of the characteristics of life is replication. In favorable conditions, the organism replicating the fastest will out-compete all other organisms. So there is no motivation or stimulus of some sort needed (or possible), by their very nature cells are made to divide as soon as feasible.<\/p>\n","answer_id":5272,"question_id":5268,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/5268/why-do-living-organisms-replicate-itself-or-procreate","last_activity_date":1423688176,"creation_date":1353403335,"answer_count":2,"title":"Why do living organisms replicate itself or procreate","body":"<p>Why do living organisms spontaneously replicate itself or \"procreate\" (my understanding is that it does).<\/p>\n\n<p>From a uni-cellular and micro-organism point of view. Is there some sort of stimulant in the environment? A chemical reaction that causes it? Is is there a physical or emotional motivation? Is it by choice?<\/p>\n\n<p>Note: I may have some terms used wrongly as I am not a biologist. In this question, I am interested at living organism nearer the forms of single smallest unit of life form.<\/p>\n","question_id":5268,"tags":["biochemistry","cell-biology","abiogenesis"],"score":0,"accepted_answer_id":5272,"down_vote_count":0,"protected_date":1423656398,"is_answered":true,"view_count":724,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3f7407d4cdbd3a90d0a9ee44498c23ad?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":238,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/238/gabriel-fair","reputation":1818,"display_name":"Gabriel Fair","accept_rate":81},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jlp4Q.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5198,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5198/anongoodnurse","reputation":12148,"display_name":"anongoodnurse"},"score":6,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1423682330,"creation_date":1423624053,"body":"<p>There is viral DNA within our genomes. Embedded in the genomes of all vertebrates are the proviral remnants of previous retroviral infections. It is possible that some have conferred biological benefits.<\/p>\n\n<p>Human endogenous retroviruses (HERVs) represent the proviral phase of exogenous retroviruses that have integrated into the germ line of their host. They are transmitted vertically through the germline and are thus inherited by successive generations in a Mendelian manner.<\/p>\n\n<p>HERVs possess a similar genomic organisation to present day exogenous retroviruses such as human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and human T cell leukaemia virus.<\/p>\n\n<p>Although many are defective through the accumulation of mutations, deletions, and termination signals, some HERVs have been implicated in certain autoimmune diseases and cancers and might have a role in the etiology and pathology of disease. <\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Within humans, the most recently active ERVs are members of the HERV-K (HML2) family. This family first integrated into the genome of the common ancestor of humans and Old World monkeys at least 30 million years ago, and it contains >12 elements that have integrated since the divergence of humans and chimpanzees, as well as at least two that are polymorphic among humans.<\/p>\n  \n  <p>Here we show that the HERV-K (HML2) family has increased in copy number predominantly via reinfection, and that the family has probably retained replication-competent and infectious members for >30 million years. We also present evidence for persistent reinfection by other ERV families within the human genome, and suggest <em>that endogenous retrovirus families are often capable of extremely long periods of smoldering infection<\/em>.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p><sub><a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC387345/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Long-term reinfection of the human genome by endogenous retroviruses<\/a><\/sub><br>\n<sub><a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8643549/\" rel=\"nofollow\">The viruses in all of us: characteristics and biological significance of human endogenous retrovirus sequences<\/a><\/sub><br>\n<sub><a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1187282/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Demystified . . . Human endogenous retroviruses<\/a><\/sub><\/p>\n","answer_id":28496,"question_id":28483,"up_vote_count":6,"last_edit_date":1423682330}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/28483/are-some-virus-loads-introduced-to-human-cell-but-never-triggered","last_activity_date":1423682330,"creation_date":1423595744,"answer_count":1,"title":"Are some virus loads introduced to human cell but never triggered?","body":"<p>Is there a term or any evidence of phage DNA integrating into chromosomes/ DNA but never being triggered? <\/p>\n\n<p>For example, could a virus that affected Neanderthals still infect human cells today but is never expressed, triggered, or executed?<\/p>\n\n<p>How often is latent viral DNA ignored by the host?<\/p>\n","question_id":28483,"tags":["pathology","virology","retrovirus","lentivirus"],"score":3,"accepted_answer_id":28496,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":44,"up_vote_count":3},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4b6eac368964ea096f57cb1dbb989a20?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":13417,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13417/edward","reputation":136,"display_name":"Edward"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ae0014e2b5be5ac76e0892cdd6f72e8e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6289,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6289/l-b","reputation":764,"display