s not change the speed of the reaction, nor does it change the rection enthalpy or the quilibrium of the reaction. See the figure for clarification (from <a href=\"http://www.uic.edu/classes/bios/bios100/lectures/enzymes.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a>):<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/KQSgM.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p>Without the enzyme the Ea (activation energy) would be so high, that the reaction would be possible in the cell. Either because this high amount of energy is not available or because the amount of energy would destroy the cell or the reaction. So the lowering of Ea allows this specific reaction to take place.<\/p>\n","answer_id":28429,"question_id":28420,"up_vote_count":3},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/s3x49.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3865,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3865/jwdietrich","reputation":252,"display_name":"jwdietrich"},"score":5,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1423420063,"creation_date":1423420063,"body":"<p>Enzymes have two benefits over raising the temperature:<\/p>\n\n<p>First, reducing the activation energy by reusable enzymes is far more energy-efficient, apart from the fact that the required temperature would vary for different reactions.<\/p>\n\n<p>Second, enzymes are able to be controlled by allosteric mechanisms, which facilitates metabolic control by feedback loops, feedforward motivs and receptor-mediated processes. In the example of glycolysis this enables the cell to fine-control its supply with energy equivalents (see figure from <a href=\"http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Glycolysis_regul_muscle.png\">Wikimedia Commons<\/a> below). This mechanism may be the most important function of enzymes.<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/7n6TQ.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Reference<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>William C. Plaxton: <a href=\"http://media.johnwiley.com.au/product_data/excerpt/0X/04714109/047141090X.pdf\">Principles of Metabolic Control<\/a>. In Kenneth B. Storey (ed.): Functional Metabolism: Regulation and Adaptation, John Wiley &amp; Sons, Inc. 2004<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","answer_id":28440,"question_id":28420,"up_vote_count":5},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/bS3hE.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3703,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3703/inf3rno","reputation":2903,"display_name":"inf3rno","accept_rate":50},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1423676525,"creation_date":1423582918,"body":"<p>By reactions there is an energy barrier called <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Activation_energy\" rel=\"nofollow\">activation energy<\/a>. Your substrate molecules have kinetic energy (they move, rotate, etc...), so when they collide properly, their kinetic energy can be used to overcome the activation energy and so the reaction takes place. According to the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arrhenius_equation\" rel=\"nofollow\">Arrhenius equation<\/a> the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reaction_rate\" rel=\"nofollow\">reaction rate<\/a> depends on the temperature, which is evident, because the kinetic energy of your molecules is higher by higher temperature. Enzymes lower the activation energy, because they help the substrates to collide with the proper orientation.<\/p>\n\n<p>Enzymes are mostly composed of amino acid chains. These chains must have proper <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Protein_folding\" rel=\"nofollow\">folding<\/a>. Increasing (or decreasing) the temperature can disrupt this folding and make the enzyme useless. This inactivation can be reversible or irreversible depending on the enzyme type, the temperature and other environmental factors e.g. pressure, osmotic pressure, etc...<\/p>\n\n<p>To answer your question, every enzyme have an optimum working temperature. At this temperature the inactivation is slow enough to be compensated by the increased reaction rate.<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/Dj9Pe.gif\" alt=\"optimum temperature\"><\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>figure 1 -  optimum temperature of a single enzyme - <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/bitesize/standard/biology/investigating_cells/enzymes_and_aerobic_respiration/revision/5/\" rel=\"nofollow\">ref<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/Ca3VD.jpg\" alt=\"optimum temperatures of multiple enzymes\"><\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>figure 2 - optimum temperatures of multiple enzymes - <a href=\"http://classes.midlandstech.edu/carterp/courses/bio225/chap06/Microbial%20Growth%20ss1.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">ref<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","answer_id":28477,"question_id":28420,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1423676525}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/28420/what-advantage-does-an-enzyme-serve-over-catalysis-by-the-addition-of-heat-energ","last_activity_date":1423676525,"creation_date":1423361320,"answer_count":3,"title":"What advantage does an enzyme serve over catalysis by the addition of heat energy?","body":"<p>I understand that an enzyme lowers the activation energy, allowing the reaction to run faster, however I am not sure, how it may be favorable during the addition of heat energy. Wouldn't that lower the activity of the enzyme since the enzyme is sensitive to heat?<\/p>\n","question_id":28420,"tags":["cell-biology"],"score":5,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":421,"up_vote_count":5},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-vdaBlcGXJFs/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAABuM/Nf09P1TsxII/photo.jpg?sz=128","user_type":"registered","user_id":13071,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13071/moon-crawlervg","reputation":21,"display_name":"Moon CrawlerVG"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christi