e body metabolism is tuned down (this is not as efficient as the adaptation to cold region - as the metabolism can't be turned down below a certain limit - this will result in death) a little and heat generation is somewhat reduced. The second and more efficient mechanism is the heat dissipation by sweating and through skin (directly).<\/p><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>Ectotherms on the other hand, do not have efficient temperature regulation systems. <\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><p>In warm regions when the temperature is high, the ectotherms seek shade and low-temperature areas to prevent over-heating<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>In cool regions they seek sunlight and expose themselves to the sunlight for warmth. For the same reason, they can also search out and stay near fire pits, campfires etc...<\/p><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>So when we calculate the energy demands, the ectotherms need more energy as they regulate their own metabolisms to match the need. <\/p>\n\n<p>The increase in need for energy in hot condition maybe due to:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>The extra-processes that are regulated like sweating, increased peripheral vasodilation - thereby increasing circulatory rate (increased work for heart)<\/li>\n<li>This thermo-regulation inturn affects other processes and systems like electrolyte and water balance, excretory system, endocrine system, thrist, etc...<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>During the cold season increased metabolism itself is the main cause for increased need for energy.<\/p>\n","answer_id":28436,"question_id":28431,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jIVNS.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":10132,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10132/sentient","reputation":111,"display_name":"Sentient","accept_rate":60},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1423445328,"creation_date":1423445328,"body":"<p>An ectotherm is an [cold-blooded] organism which is dependent on external sources of body heat. They do not need to regularly consume food to warm their bodies. As a result, they can subsist on lower metabolic rates and varying internal temperatures (poikilothermy). However, physical activity is restricted to certain hours (night) and or habitats; ectotherms tend to be rapidly exhausted.<\/p>\n\n<p>An endotherm is an [warm-blooded] organism which is dependent on the interal generation of heat. To maintain consistent temperatures (homeothermy), they must regularly consume food for metabolism. This also allows for a greater work capacity than ectotherms. Physical activity is not limited to certain hours and or habitats. <\/p>\n","answer_id":28446,"question_id":28431,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/28431/why-do-endotherms-need-more-food-than-ectotherms","last_activity_date":1423445328,"creation_date":1423398292,"answer_count":2,"title":"Why do endotherms need more food than ectotherms?","body":"<p>I have a rough idea: its as endotherms need more food to keep their temperature stable whilst ectotherms use less of their food in respiration, but that's just me parroting the textbook I don't really understand it. Could someone help out? Thank you.<\/p>\n","question_id":28431,"tags":["temperature","homeostasis"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":true,"view_count":2017,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/506084fa293b055fd627f9e41b4c0f2a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5168,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5168/ezrock","reputation":121,"display_name":"ezrock"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/506084fa293b055fd627f9e41b4c0f2a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5168,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5168/ezrock","reputation":121,"display_name":"ezrock"},"score":0,"post_id":13982,"edited":false,"creation_date":1387066325,"comment_id":18298,"body":"I&#39;d give this a veterinary ta