 been prepared from the beginning and kept that way throughout life or till a certain point. But why make and break it every month? (The breaking of this preparation is the cause of menstrual pain, which is what I'm worried about).<\/p>\n","question_id":28405,"tags":["human-biology","pain","reproductive-biology"],"score":2,"accepted_answer_id":28415,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":true,"view_count":65,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1423326213},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7974275b33c1c13d775152e812b35776?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":558,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/558/kirby","reputation":619,"display_name":"Kirby","accept_rate":52},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/TVDAK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":69,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/69/rory-m","reputation":9094,"display_name":"Rory M","accept_rate":88},"score":0,"post_id":1479,"edited":false,"creation_date":1332083420,"comment_id":1831,"body":"You have now got sufficient rep to avoid new user restrictions so can post inline images yourself - you can either do this manually using <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/editing-help#images\">markdown<\/a> or there is a button on the WYSIWYG editor :)"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/TVDAK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":69,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/69/rory-m","reputation":9094,"display_name":"Rory M","accept_rate":88},"score":6,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1332083015,"creation_date":1332083015,"body":"<p>Starting with the left hand side of the diagram:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><em>III:2<\/em> is definitely a carrier (Tt) as one parent (<em>II:2<\/em>) is affected (tt).<\/li>\n<li><em>III:1<\/em> is also definitely a carrier (Tt) as when mating with <em>III:2<\/em> they produce an affected (tt) offspring (<em>IV:1<\/em>)<\/li>\n<li>This means that we can work out the possibilities for <em>IV:4<\/em> as we know the parent genotypes.  It follows the standard arrangement for two carrier parents giving the options of:\n<ul>\n<li>TT (1/4)<\/li>\n<li>Tt (2/4 = 1/2)<\/li>\n<li>tt (Normally 1/4 but in this case 0 as individual not marked as affected). <\/li>\n<\/ul><\/li>\n<li>Therefore for this scenario, the probabilities for <em>IV:4<\/em> are :\n<ul>\n<li>TT (1/3)<\/li>\n<li>Tt (2/3)<\/li>\n<\/ul><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>Now if we look at the right hand side of the diagram.<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><em>IV:5<\/em> is definitely a carrier (Tt) as one of their parents (<em>III:5<\/em>) is affected.  <\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>This gives two possible Punnett squares to be examined:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\n|                                         (IV:5)                               |\n|                          T                                   t                |\n|            -------------------------------------------------------------------|\n|           |                                |                                  |\n|         T |              TT                |                Tt                |\n|           |                                |                                  |\n| (IV:4)    |-------------------------------------------------------------------|\n|          |                                |                                  |\n|         T |              TT                |                Tt                |\n|           |                                |                                  |\n|-----------|-------------------------------------------------------------------|\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>This gives nil affected offspring so we can disregard this option for your question (as we are ONLY looking for scenarios which produce affected individuals).<\/p>\n\n<p>Therefore the alternative is:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\n|                                         (IV:5)                               |\n|                          T                                   t                |\n|            -------------------------------------------------------------------|\n|           |                                |                                  |\n|         T |              TT                |                Tt                |\n|           |                                |                                  |\n| (IV:4)    |-------------------------------------------------------------------|\n|          |                                |                                  |\n|         t |              TT                |                tt                |\n|           |                                |                                  |\n|-----------|-------------------------------------------------------------------|\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Giving 1/4 affected offspring.  <\/p>\n\n<p>As mentioned above, in order to have affected offspring then <em>IV:4<\/em> <strong>must<\/strong> be Tt.  There is a <code>2/3<\/code> chance of this being the case.  If this is the case, then there is a <code>1/4<\/code> chance of the child being tt. <\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Both<\/strong> conditions need to be true for this to happen so we multiply the fractions:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>2/3 * 1/4 = 1/6\n<\/code><\/pre>\n","answer_id":1480,"question_id":1479,"up_vote_count":6}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/1479/pedigree-probability-of-autosomal-recessive-trait","last_activity_date":1423341242,"creation_date":1332077208,"answer_count":1,"title":"Pedigree Probability of Autosomal Recessive Trait","body":"<p>Here is a pedigree: <\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/566Pu.png\" alt=\"Pedigree Chart\"><\/p>\n\n<p>The trait is autosomal recessive.<\/p>\n\n<p>The question is:  What is the probability that the bottom 2 people (4 and 5) have a child with the trait?<\/p>\n\n<p>I tried doing <code>2/3 * 2/3 * 2/3 *1/4<\/code> and got <code>2/27<\/code> but this is wrong. I thought that the probability of III 1 being a carrier is 2/3.  The probability that IV 4 is a carrier is also 2/3.  The probability that III 6 is a carrier is 2/3 and IV 5 must be a carrier.  So IV 4 and IV 5 must be carriers.  The probability that they have a child with the trait is 1/4. But I am not getting the right answer.<\/p>\n\n<p>The right answer is 1/6.<\/p>\n","question_id":1479,"tags":["genetics","homework","genetic-diagrams"],"score":4,"accepted_answer_id":1480,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":16533,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1332083133},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/vnYni.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1916,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1916/mysky","reputation":1053,"display_name":"MySky","accept_rate":76},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/DNPz8.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":11841,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11841/one-face","reputation":2241,"display_name":"One Face","accept_rate":73},"score":0,"post_id":28294,"edited":false,"creation_date":1422974597,"comment_id":46347,"body":"I have edited your question a bit. Please feel free to roll back if this does not suit you"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fcf9d3bdac2c3fa35177730c31b34f79?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6307,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6307/canadianer","reputation":6147,"display_name":"canadianer"},"score":0,"post_id":28294,"edited":false,"creation_date":1422976498,"comment_id":46348,"body":"Homology, ESTs, codon usage, length of ORF"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/11ecb2130d870caa97f33b9e9e658e19?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4109,"link":"http:/