ates of\n  another candidate ORF, the longer one is reported. However, a single\n  transcript can report multiple ORFs (allowing for operons, chimeras,\n  etc).<\/li>\n  <li>optional the putative peptide has a match to a Pfam domain above the\n  noise cutoff score.<\/li>\n  <\/ul>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>So in essence, look for the longest ORF, and then use some secondary metric (hidden Markov model, position weight array, database query, etc) to refine your prediction. <\/p>\n","answer_id":28412,"question_id":28294,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/28294/how-do-biologists-infer-correct-orf-of-a-dna-sequence","last_activity_date":1423332262,"creation_date":1422970405,"answer_count":1,"title":"How do biologists infer correct ORF of a DNA sequence?","body":"<p>Each DNA (RNA) sequence has 6 possible Open Reading Frames(ORF). My question is: What are the theoretical bases of <em>in vitro<\/em> or <em>in silico<\/em> tries to find correct reading frame of a sequence?<\/p>\n\n<p>Is it just distance between Start and Stop codons, or are there some other factors with more important impacts in this subject?<\/p>\n","question_id":28294,"tags":["transcription","sequence-analysis","orf"],"score":5,"accepted_answer_id":28412,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":123,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1422984536},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/RX4y7.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":10056,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10056/larry-m","reputation":113,"display_name":"Larry M."},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":0,"post_id":23710,"edited":false,"creation_date":1415146494,"comment_id":37396,"body":"Highly unlikely and I dare to say impossible. Maybe he mean